e":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1730"},{"type":"tags","id":"1731"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"2067"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26784"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63504"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78082"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman complains of tingling in her hands and feet, 24 hours post-op after a total thyroidectomy for a follicular thyroid carcinoma. Her symptoms rapidly progress to severe muscle cramps, laryngeal stridor, and convulsions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following laboratory findings would be expected in this patient prior to treatment of the current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased serum calcium and decreased PTH","Decreased serum calcium and increased PTH","Increased serum calcium and decreased PTH","Increased serum calcium and increased PTH","Normal serum calcium and decreased PTH"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHypocalcaemia is a potential complication after thyroid surgery. It usually occurs in the first days after surgery and it can be symptomatic or asymptomatic. The main cause of hypocalcaemia is an acute parathyroid insufficiency due to a reduction of the functioning parathyroid parenchyma. Impaired PTH secretion leads to postoperative hypocalcaemia by inhibiting bone resorption and reducing 1,25-dihydroxy vitamin D synthesis in the kidney, resulting in reduced intestinal absorption of calcium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn early postoperative \u003Cstrong\u003Edecrease in serum iPTH concentrations associated with a serum-Ca \u0026lt;8 mg/dL \u003C/strong\u003Ehas been shown in several post-operative cases. The reduction of the functioning parathyroid tissue is secondary to intraoperative damage to the parathyroid glands caused by a combination of factors such as mechanical or thermal trauma, gland devascularisation, obstruction of venous outflow, inadvertent parathyroid excision, and parathyroid autotransplantation. Other factors that may contribute to the development of post-thyroidectomy hypocalcaemia include haemodilution, urinary calcium excretion facilitated by surgical stress, calcitonin release due to thyroid manipulation, vitamin D deficiency, and hungry bone syndrome (this is usually only seen in patients having parathyroid surgery for renal disease).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETiming of serum-Ca measurement after thyroidectomy is critical because it has an impact on the prevalence of hypocalcaemia rates: the closer the blood sampling is performed to surgery the lower the rates of hypocalcaemia will be. On the other hand, if serum-Ca is determined too late, patients may develop clinical symptoms before treatment is commenced. Most patients undergoing total thyroidectomy will have their PTH \u0026amp; Ca levels monitored on the evening of surgery, and again the following morning to evaluate both the absolute levels and trends. Ongoing frequency of monitoring will depend on these blood results and the patients\u0027 symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Postoperative hypocalcaemia is a relatively common complication after total thyroidectomy.","Impaired PTH secretion leads to postoperative hypocalcaemia by inhibiting bone resorption and reducing 1,25-dihydroxy vitamin D synthesis in the kidney resulting in reduced intestinal absorption of calcium.","Parathyroid hormone (PTH) is crucial for maintaining calcium homeostasis, and its deficiency can lead to hypocalcaemia."],"references":["Lorente-Poch L, Sancho JJ, Mu\u00f1oz-Nova JL, S\u00e1nchez-Vel\u00e1zquez P, Sitges-Serra A. Defining the syndromes of parathyroid failure after total thyroidectomy. Gland Surg. 2015 Feb;4(1):82-90. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2227-684X.2014.12.04. PMID: 25713783; PMCID: PMC4321048. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25713783/","Antakia R, Edafe O, Uttley L, Balasubramanian SP. Effectiveness of preventative and other surgical measures on hypocalcemia following bilateral thyroid surgery: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Thyroid. 2015 Jan;25(1):95-106. doi: 10.1089/thy.2014.0101. PMID: 25203484. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25203484/","Puzziello A, Rosato L, Innaro N, Orlando G, Avenia N, Perigli G, Cal\u00f2 PG, De Palma M. Hypocalcemia following thyroid surgery: incidence and risk factors. A longitudinal multicenter study comprising 2,631 patients. Endocrine. 2014 Nov;47(2):537-42. doi: 10.1007/s12020-014-0209-y. Epub 2014 Feb 22. PMID: 24563161. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24563161/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63504"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11991"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63504"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T13:19:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T13:20:40+10:30","number":6,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-01-09T13:19:54+10:30","plagiarismScore":70.6,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4581-6.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T215153Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=477db3308a9c4ba9cc47eb6c1d041f6d1aed1771fbce2c6c74510a6d12d4b55f"},"relationships":{"item":